Do you have a black box in your car?
While American road designers are trying to find the money to repair a crumbling highway system, many are starting to see the solution in a small black box neatly arranged on the dashboard of your car.
These devices, which track every mile traveled by a motorist and pass this information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt to modernize America’s outdated highway financing system, undertaken by Washington and state planning bodies.
Usually, the boring arena of highway planning unexpectedly gave rise to intense debates and colorful alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you travel and even perhaps where you travel them — and then use that information when drawing up tax accounts.
Tea-drinking movement in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of questions regarding privacy.
And while Congress can’t yet agree whether to continue or not, several states aren’t going to wait.
They’re thinking about how over the next decade it’s possible to move to a system where drivers pay for every mile of road they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already taken these black boxes for testing, some of which have the function of satellite tracking.
This is really necessary for our country.
“It’s not a question we can have a choice on,” said Hassan Ihrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which is preparing plans to begin tracking the state’s miles traveled by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in how we pay these taxes.
The technology for this already exists.
The need for this is compounded by the lack of funds from the Government Fund for Highway Construction, funded by taxes that Americans pay on gas stations.
Americans don’t buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars travel more miles per gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not risen for 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise taxes even by one cent at high gasoline prices.
“The gasoline tax is simply impossible to keep,” said Lee Mannich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices were recently installed on cars to test the payment system.
“This will be the best alternative in the long term,” he said.
Borrowing is called a bad user fee.
It is not surprising that this idea attracts urban liberals, since with the help of taxes it will be possible to change the nature of travel to reduce the load of roads and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
The planning authorities in California are looking at this system in the course of developing strategies to achieve the targets set by the ambitious laws of this state to combat global warming.
However, House Rep. Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also sees the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free-market supporters at the Reason Foundation are also thrilled to have drivers pay for every mile.
“It’s not just a tax that’s going to go into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, Reason’s vice president of policy.
People pay directly for what they get.
The move is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers who in 2011 called on Congress to move toward a fair payment.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved about 10,000 cars.
However, House leaders rejected the proposal because of concerns from rural lawmakers representing voters who often have to travel many miles in their daily lives to get to work or to the city.
Several states and cities, however, go this route on their own.
The greatest enthusiasm is shown in the state of Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are attracted to participate in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state for miles of mileage instead of gasoline tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
It is being considered in New York.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis with the participation of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport departments of 17 East Coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how they will be able to make these changes.
This concept has not been universally accepted.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently equipped with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track their every move.
“Worrying about ‘big brother’ and things like that is a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and efficiency management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn't what people wanted.
When the trials were in full swing, the Nevada branch of the American Civil Liberties Union warned on its website: “It will be quite easy to turn these devices into full-scale tracking devices.”
There is no need to create a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to store records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of several states where the search for low-cost technology is going on, which would allow state authorities to count the miles traveled by car, but without information about the place and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more at ease.
The search for this technology led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, this company was not involved in the collection of state taxes.
It sought to enter the developing market of the type of auto insurance, in which drivers pay on the basis of mileage.
But the devices it tests attract road designers because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information periodically downloaded using a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed and track their location,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There have been a few big mistakes in some of these state pilot programs.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with providing drivers with different options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they can completely abandon the device, deciding instead to pay a fixed fee based on the average number of miles that all residents of the state travel.
Elsewhere, they hope to sell the idea to a wary public, forcing devices to do more, not less.
In New York City, transport officials are keen to develop a taxing device that will also charge parking meters, provide “pay as you drive” insurance, and collect a pool of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Automotiveists will be attracted to the participation of the benefits that will be offered to them,” the city planning document says.
Some transport system designers, however, are wondering if all the talk of making a payment is just a huge distraction.
At the San Francisco Bay Area City Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the Trust Fund for Highway Construction by raising gasoline taxes.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on drivers of hybrid cars and other persons whose vehicles do not use a lot of gasoline to pay their fair share.
“There’s no need for radical surgery when all you need to do is take aspirin,” Randy Rentschler, director of the Commission on Legislation and Public Relations, said in a statement.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their privacy and a lot of other things.
EU prepares measures to support Ukraine in case of economic pressure from Russia
The European Union has a contingency plan to provide Ukraine with gas, as well as to reach an agreement with the IMF on an emergency loan if Russia takes any measures in response to the possible signing of the EU-Ukraine Association Agreement at the Vilnius Summit.
A stand-by loan is being negotiated with the IMF, and another EU official directly involved in the negotiations added that their goal is to reach an agreement soon.
In addition to the potential loan from the IMF, Ukraine can receive 610 million euros from the European Union itself.
Analysts polled by Reuters doubt that Ukraine and the IMF are able to overcome long-standing disagreements about the terms of funding.
It does not believe in the possibility of reforms necessary to receive assistance, and the international rating agency S&P, which on Friday lowered Ukraine's sovereign rating by one degree - to "B-" with "B".
However, EU officials say that the IMF can show flexibility in terms of lending, taking into account the circumstances of Ukraine.
In addition to the country’s financial support plan, the EU has a backup option to provide Ukraine with gas, the vast majority of which is now coming from Russia.
Perhaps it will be gas from the Nord Stream or reverse from Slovakia.
The latter, according to officials, is the most possible and acceptable way in case Russia “isolates” Ukraine.
Analysts believe that such a method of reverse deliveries to Ukraine can be used only for a few weeks, and will likely lead to a decrease in deliveries to other regions.
“Negotiations are being held between EU countries and Ukrainians on how to create favorable conditions for Ukraine to import gas from other sources, not from Russia, or from the same source, but on other routes,” the source added.
Russia out of the fight for pollution of cities by cars
Attempts to solve the transport problems of large cities have been observed in most of the world’s megacities since the second half of the 20th century.
As a rule, it was either about their redevelopment and expansion of highways, or about attempts to reduce the demand for road trips, the number of cars and the time of their use.
There is a well-known example of Singapore, where a strict quota has been introduced for the increase in the number of private cars, and the right to purchase them is bought at auctions.
Its price can be two to three times higher than the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have introduced a fee for entering the city centre.
In Germany, for example in Hamburg and Stuttgart, the so-called green zones are introduced, where entry is allowed only for cars with a certain eco-class, also using high-quality fuel (including biofuels or electric vehicles).
Beijing’s Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved a “five-year clean air plan” in 2012 with a total cost of about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
According to Li Kunsheng, director of the transport pollution control department of the Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau, the main goal of the five-year plan is to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, increase the number of private cars to the level of not more than 6 million vehicles (now 5.2 million), and also increase the use of more than one vehicle.
According to the agency, now motor transport in Beijing is responsible for 22.5% of the total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program is the restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, the urban measures of the "green five-year" include the development of an accelerated compared with the rest of the country of the electric vehicle transition to the euro standards of fuel, the introduction of the local system of eco-standards and marking of cars and fuel, the restriction on the entry of cars into the central part of the city, the ban on the use of obsolete vehicles (except for the creation of old vehicles).
The number of car innovations in Beijing also includes a ban for all private cars to move within the fifth ring of traffic (only in the capital of China, the number of cars is six) one day a week (the corresponding information is contained in the license plate of the vehicle), as well as the issuance of registration marks for cars on the basis of the lottery (in the first year, the number of cars in the second year, the number of cars in the third year).
According to the current state program "Environmental protection for 2012-2020", the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Nature, in 2011, “moving sources” accounted for 41% of all emissions of pollutants into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial emissions, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
In Russia, they are just beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
The Director of the Institute of Transport Economics and Transport Policy of the HSE Mikhail Blinkin believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for road trips - a matter that is notoriously unpopular, they can be adopted by society only on the condition of their complete universality.
In the case of Moscow, there is a unique problem related to the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters weakly sensitive to any regulatory influences - business and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, the total number of which is not less than 200 thousand. (about 5% of the total number of cars).
Recently, urbanists from the ECOM center in St. Petersburg prepared a study that analyzes the balance of urban areas between residential construction, the area of road coverage and the amount of road transport.
The main conclusions of the researchers: the city center is provided with roads twice less than required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in the parking lot or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed not to build parking lots, but car storage, not to expand, but to reduce the traffic part (so that the streets become more pedestrian-friendly), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal transport within the territory of the security zone of the historic center (the total area of about 3212 hectares, covering the city center).
