Goldman Sachs warns of risks to the Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks for the main driver of fragile economic growth in Russia - consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payment on unsecured consumer loans and massive reductions in workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed, but rather, the structure of that growth.
Recently, it is completely conditioned by consumption, which almost does not slow down the turnover, "said the chief economist of Goldman Sachs on Russia Clemens Grafe, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
The nominal wage growth in Russia is now about 10%.
With inflation of 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at about the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so most likely, they will be engaged in the optimization of personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - by only 2%, - explained Mr. Grafe.
The companies have been faced with a reduction in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to layoffs and an increase in unemployment.
Russian business can not raise wages, comments the chief economist of Barclays Capital on Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyushin.
Unemployment near historical lows, competition for workers is high.
In order to lure employees away from the side or keep current ones, employers have to raise wages.
Consumption in Russia of podder is alive and very fast growth of demand credit.
According to Mr. Graf, due to the extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplier effect on the country's economy.
“We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of demand lending, the money is not spent on the economy, but returned to the same banks in the form of interest payments,” the economist said.
But the problem is another - at Goldman Sachs expect an increase in overdue on unsecured loans.
They are mostly taken by poor people who have nothing to provide for them.
Interest rates on such loans are high.
As a result, they are often not returned,” said Mr Grafe.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payment on unsecured loans.
Vasily Solodkov, director of the HSE Banking Institute, is already seeing signs of a looming banking crisis.
Small credit organizations, without access to the cheap resources that state banks have, were forced to attract public funds at high interest rates.
In response, state banks went on the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rate, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If state banks do not give up dumping, Russia faces a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
Deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks, the economist considers a harbinger of mass collapse.
"The state banks themselves will not cope with such a situation: the deposit insurance system was not originally designed for a systemic crisis," the head of the institute warns.
But consumption growth will slow down without a crisis of non-payments, believe the investment bank, - due to the refusal to index salaries of civil servants and military, laid in the current version of the draft budget.
Partly the impact on consumption will be mitigated by freezing tariffs on natural monopolies (and, as a consequence, by lowering inflation).
But only partially: if investments do not grow (and the prerequisite for this is not yet - see the certificate), the growth of consumption will still slow down, I am sure at Goldman Sachs.
Vladimir Pantyushin of Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is still falling oil prices,” he says.
According to him, the economy of Russia will begin to decline at the cost of oil below $ 90 / bar.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the central bank is not yet able to lower interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has fallen, and banks have started to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting," Clemens Grafe said.
The interest policy of the Central Bank on market rates does not affect, only affects the rates of interbank lending.
“For the Central Bank, this is a collapse of all hope,” said Clemens Grafe.
The money received at the auctions of the Central Bank, banks use not to credit the economy, but to manage their liquidity
As soon as the rate decreases, the exchange rate immediately changes, this means that the funds are trying to go to speculation against the ruble.
“Sooner or later, the Central Bank will understand that this strategy does not work,” Grafe said, recalling that the state plans to release the ruble in “free swimming” by the end of 2015.
But it will either have to do it sooner or raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he believes.
According to him, the ruble rate is now artificially exceeded by 10%.
There is only one way to lose weight, the expert concludes.
But if the central bank plunges into financiers, even if the shadow of doubt is that the elimination of the currency corridor is not part of the policy of weakening the ruble, it can bring down the ruble much stronger.
