Snowden is ready to “cooperate” with Germany on U.S. intelligence
Edward Snowden, a U.S. intelligence whistleblower, said he was ready to go to Berlin to testify before the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director, Keith Alexander, could not answer questions about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Str<0xC3><0xB6>bele met with Mr Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he was granted asylum to discuss his testimony in Germany.
A letter from Mr. Snowden, which the deputy presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, said: “Although the result of my efforts has been clearly positive, my government continues to treat dissent as a betrayal and seeks to criminalize political statements with criminal charges that give no protection.”
But speaking the truth is not a crime.
In the letter, Mr. Snowden said he believes the support of the international community could persuade the U.S. government to drop criminal charges against him.
The charges brought by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, Germany’s interior minister, told Zeit Online: “If Mr. Snowden is ready to talk to German officials, we will find ways to make that possible.”
Relations between the United States and Germany have become strained after allegations that the NSA was listening to Chancellor Angela Merkel’s phone.
Thomas Opperman, a deputy who heads the parliamentary group that oversees the intelligence service, said that if there is an opportunity to hear Mr. Snowden as a witness, “without endangering him and destroying relations with the United States completely,” it should be used.
Mr. Str<0xC3><0xB6>bele, Member of Parliament for the Green Party of Germany, posted his photo with Mr. Snowden on his Twitter.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Str<0xC3><0xB6>bele said that, according to a lawyer for a former NSA contractor, Mr. Snowden would not be able to return to Russia if he left.
If Mr Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would need assurances that he would be there “safe,” the deputy said.
Mr. Snowden said in his letter that he faced a “hard and constant” persecution campaign that forced him to leave his home.
However, he said he was inspired by the world’s response to “his political statements.”
Citizens around the world, as well as high-ranking officials — including in the United States — have found the disclosure of an unchecked system of pervasive surveillance useful to society.
The letter proposes to cooperate with the German authorities “when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation will be solved”.
Frontier Airlines will charge a fee for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, though their announcement on Wednesday said passengers would be able to keep the entire bank.
The new hand luggage fee applies to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 if travelers would pay only if they found themselves at the exit for boarding.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee should force passengers to take care of payment in advance.
“We don’t want to charge for that,” she said.
The airlines began charging for the first and second bags delivered to baggage in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges are stuffing as much as they can in hand luggage placed in the upper baggage compartments, which is why there is often a lack of space in these compartments.
Fees are one way to get passengers to spend less on board.
O'Malley said that this new levy is not really for the purpose of making money.
The fact is that the most loyal Frontier customers say that finding a place in the top luggage compartments is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who buy tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in the queue at the departure of the Frontier flight may be able to carry the bag for free, while the next passenger in the queue may pay $100 for the same bag.
O'Malley said the change in procedures on the Frontier website and at the Frontier check-in counters was intended to ensure that passengers would be aware of the fare before they got to boarding.
The new Frontier manual storage fee will not begin to be charged until the summer, although the date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage fees and other fees, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money, and passengers who need this service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street consider the addition of baggage fees a sign that airlines are charging enough money to cover the cost of air travel after several years of losses.
However, most of them did not relate to manual storage fees.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first manual baggage claim three years ago, and another Allegiant Air discounter later followed suit.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
According to his estimate in a December 2011 report, the manual deposit fee brings Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorensen, the former top manager of Midwest Airlines, recently flew a Spirit flight, and he was curious to find out what he would find on the way out when passengers encountered the unusual Spirit hand luggage collection.
“The landing process was the smoothest I’ve seen in my career with airlines,” he said.
I was expecting to see teeth scraping and a fight at the exit to the landing.
The plane was full, he said, “and the landing went fast.”
Frontier also follows Spirit for a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda, or juice.
Frontier said that passengers who receive soda or juice can keep the entire bank and that coffee will be provided free of charge.
It will continue to provide water for free.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for drinks in 2008, but declined to do so after seven months, after passengers began to complain and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier’s initiative to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not buy tickets directly from the airline is its latest measure to attract customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket sellers, such as Orbitz, $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them, rather than turning to an online travel agency.
However, Frontier went further in this area.
In September, it began giving twice as many frequent flyer bonus miles to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, it cut the premium number of miles to 25 percent of the miles traveled.
For example, a 1,000-mile trip with Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would allow you to get 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can choose a seat in advance only if they buy tickets directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in her hometown of Denver, but her business is shrinking and becoming a loser.
Revenue declined 9 percent and flight capabilities declined nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic is trying to fix Frontier's finances as part of the airline's sale.
NSA blames "internal error" and not hackers in the termination of the site
The undercover National Security Agency said Friday evening that the shutdown of their site for several hours caused a technical failure, not hackers, as claimed on the network.
“NSA.gov was unavailable for several hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during the scheduled update,” the intelligence agency said in an official email.
The problem will be solved tonight.
Claims that the outage was caused by a distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack are incorrect.
Earlier this evening, online server monitoring systems registered that the NSA site did not work for at least six hours, and the site is still unavailable to some users.
Earlier, a representative of the NSA told ABC News that the agency’s internal secret network was “not at all” hacked.
No classified information is in danger, the representative said.
At least one online group of activist hackers said it was responsible for decommissioning the NSA’s website with a DDoS attack.
DDoS attacks are designed to overwhelm the target site with traffic until the servers are overloaded and the site fails.
The tactics of hackers are relatively simple, and the attacks are not designed to penetrate the internal network of the target system.
Previously, the NSA’s super-secret agent, once nicknamed “No Such Agency,” has been at the center of public attention and fierce criticism in recent months after a series of revelations about its extensive surveillance programs abroad and within the country — all a reaction to the NSA’s secret files stolen and stolen from the agent.
The growing controversy around the agency has prompted speculation that today’s incident was the result of targeted actions by hackers.
Bombardier's profit declines with drop in deliveries and number of orders for aircraft
Bombardier, a Canadian manufacturer of aircraft and trains, said on Thursday it was reducing net profit by 15 per cent as a result of the reduced number of orders and deliveries of aircraft in the third quarter and problems with contracts in its rail division.
Montreal-based Bombardier also did not release any flight test data for its newest CSeries aircraft, nor did it provide new information on whether ambitious plans to put the aircraft into commercial service by next September would be implemented.
After the first test flight of the aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, it flew only three times, which raises questions about whether the test stage is on schedule.
The results did not justify the forecasts and led to a fall in shares of more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerxen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, on Thursday downgraded his valuation from “over-medium” to “medium” because of the belief that stock growth is limited to the next quarter or two.
“Although the decline in the number of aircraft deliveries was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed with the transport department’s profit indicators,” Doerxen said in a stock market review.
We believe Bombardier will receive new orders for the CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, if new orders are not announced in the coming months, we assume that the market will be more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to gain a place in the lower price segment of the market, where Boeing and Airbus now dominate.
The first prototype of the aircraft was presented in March and made its first flight in September after several months of delay.
However, firm orders for the CSeries are not yet too many – 177, as potential buyers are waiting for the results of flight tests to verify the company’s claims about the fuel efficiency and potential economy of the new liner.
In total, there are now 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
CEO Pierre Bodouan was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft was launched into commercial operation.
On Thursday, executives also assured analysts and the media that the program is moving forward as planned.
"The test model of the aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," Bodouan said during a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned for the time of the downing of the aircraft.
All manufacturers plan the tests differently.
We decided to make the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will be the case throughout the flight test program.
The second of the five test samples is expected to make a flight in the coming weeks and all others will follow soon, the company said.
And yet analysts are skeptical of the statement that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it is estimating the time of commissioning and will provide new information in the next few months.
“This slow pace of flight testing – though apparently consistent with Bombardier’s internal schedule – reinforces our view that commissioning will be carried forward to the first quarter of 2015,” Doerxen said.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier’s net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same – 9 cents.
Gross income fell slightly, from $4.2 billion to $4.1 billion.
Analysts expected a profit of 10 cents per share and a gross income of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world’s fourth-largest aircraft manufacturer said it delivered 45 aircraft per quarter, down from 57 in the previous year.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26 aircraft.
The aerospace department’s order portfolio stood at $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31.
“In the aerospace field, the results were in line with our goals, but a small number of incoming orders and general market conditions became an unpleasant factor,” Bodwan said.
Gross revenue in the aerospace sector fell by 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world’s largest train maker, said gross revenue in the sector had risen nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The portfolio of orders in the transport division amounted to $32.6 billion as of September 30, which is slightly higher than the figure from December 31.
The revenues of the transport unit were negatively affected by the problems with the execution of several large contracts.
The management stated that a new development plan would be presented in the fourth quarter.
Shares of Bombardier, which also announced that Google Chief Financial Officer Patrick Picchett will join the board of directors, fell 8.5 percent to C$4.83 at auction in mid-Thursday.
Brazil's Embraer SA, the world's third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and Bombardier's closest competitor, said on Thursday it was cutting quarterly revenue by 10 percent.
Sony Expects Lower Annual Profits
The Japanese electronics manufacturer, Sony Corporation, having completed the previous quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, reduced its forecast for profit for the current financial year.
Sony’s results for the period July to September 2013 were more disappointing than expected due to a drop in demand for TVs, camcorders and personal computers manufactured by the Japanese corporation.
Sony's television business, which in the second quarter brought the company's first operating profit in three years of 5.2 billion yen, fell again to 9.3 billion yen in the reporting period.
Japan’s consumer electronics market is going through a tough time, especially as demand for televisions is declining.
And while competitors seek a way out of a difficult situation, Sony continues to focus on the consumer segment.
For example, one of Sony’s main rivals, Panasonic Corporation, has recently shifted its focus to industrial components: here, the company’s sales are growing at a high rate, especially due to automotive systems and environmentally friendly technologies.
As a result, by the end of the financial year, which will end in March 2014, Sony expects to receive 179 billion yen of operating profit against the previously expected 230 billion yen.
At the same time, according to Thomson Reuters, analysts assumed that the figure will be significantly higher and will amount to 221 billion yen.
In an effort to get out of the crisis, Sony is expanding its product line.
In the middle of this month, it was announced the start of sales of "smart" watches from a Japanese corporation, endowed with a number of fashionable features that will allow you to get rid of the need to deliver a smartphone 100 times a day from your pocket.
After Sony lowered its annual profit and earnings forecast, the company's shares at the opening of the torogos in Tokyo in the morning lost more than 11%, falling to 1,668 yen per share.
The gene of speech turned out to be a stimulant of the formation of synapses
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein through which the “speech gene” Foxp2 performs its function, stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its brief content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
Its role was established in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other.
Scientists have found that family members have been affected by the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function remains unknown.
In a new study, biologists have shown that at least some of its functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulator of the formation of new synapses in the brain area associated with speech formation.
This is due to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was found as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 was one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, with only Foxp2 citing its activity.
The fact that SRPX2 does affect vocalization has been confirmed by scientists in a mouse experiment.
When the animals’ gene activity was artificially reduced, they screamed less when separated from their mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of the sounds was also restored.
Previously, the mice were also shown the connection with the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
Animals that were given a human copy of the gene ate more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
Until now, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, accordingly, managed by SRPX2 is associated with purely "mechanical" sound-forming properties or more subtle processes.
A Cocaine Addiction Lawyer Who Warned the Head of a Criminal Group About a Police Investigation Is Jailed
