A lawyer nicknamed Bash and dubbed a “cool lawyer” among the criminals, he was arrested at his home in 2011 after a police operation to track Scarborough, whom he had previously represented in a drug-related court.
Officers noticed Scarborough, 32, leaving three bags of cocaine at a lawyer’s home in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was at a lawyer’s association dinner with colleagues.
The investigation revealed that Ditta was “regularly using” a Class A drug after tests showed traces of cocaine in his hair, on his wallet, and on credit cards.
For eight months from January to August 2011, he tried to illegally obtain information about the arrests of two people on behalf of Scarborough, as well as one of his accomplices.
All four suspects were under police surveillance at the time as part of a large-scale investigation into the activities of a criminal organization for the sale of heroin and cocaine in Lancashire, Cambria, Merciside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
They and 32 others were later jailed after police seized heroin and cocaine worth <0xC2><0xA3>1.5 million and more than <0xC2><0xA3>200,000 in cash during a series of raids.
The 42-year-old Ditta passed the information to the criminals for fear that his cocaine addiction would be exposed.
Today in the Liverpool Royal Court, Ditt, who works at the legal firm Forbes Solicitors, located in Blackburn, was covered with shame after admitting his guilt in two cases of deliberate obstruction of justice following a three-week trial in the Liverpool Crown Court.
He confessed to cocaine possession at one of the previous court hearings.
The lawyer’s disclosure came after police investigating Scarborough’s activities found that he had been talking to Ditt on the phone regularly since February 2011.
Two detectives tracked down the suspect and found him approaching Ditt’s home in Blackburn and placing 60 percent-purity drugs in a black golf glove under a lawyer’s trash can.
Shortly after the transfer, Scarborough repeatedly called Ditt, who was at dinner at Blackburn Rovers' Iwood Park football stadium.
The lawyer returned home after the drugs; nine conversations took place between them.
The court learned that Ditta had “regularly used” cocaine after tests found traces of the drug class A in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested, but denied using cocaine, said he had spoken to a suspected dealer because he was his client, and insisted that their communication was a “lawyer’s secret.”
During his detention, Ditta took his wallet and tried to withdraw several credit cards, but all of them were confiscated, he was also taken a hair sample.
In an interview with the police, he said that along with the workplace, he also had a home office, and clients came to his home for legal matters.
However, it became known to the court that after important arrests he had called the largest participants in the illegal drug trade, a number of which he had previously represented in court, to tell what the detectives knew about them.
In an indictment, Ann White said, “If anyone knows that the law should not be broken, it’s a criminal lawyer.”
Mr. Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal lawyer because he has entered into too close a relationship with certain clients.
The contact we are talking about is not just a drug dealer, but a drug dealer supplying drugs to his own lawyer.
Some of his conversations would certainly prove legitimate, since he was their lawyer.
However, this has largely gone beyond the normal relationship between the lawyer and the client.
He obstructed the police investigation as much as possible to allow these persons to continue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta did not honor his profession, but shamed it.
He got too close to certain clients, in particular Scarborough, and allowed himself to doubt his disinterestedness.
“If I were a corrupt lawyer that I am not and would like to pass on the information to Mr. Scarborough, I would not wait 15 hours, I would do it immediately.”
But after the meeting, Lancashire Police Senior Officer Lee Halstead said, “Mr. Ditta turned from a criminal lawyer into a criminal as soon as he began to acquire drugs from organized crime representatives.”
His addiction to cocaine had made him hopelessly compromised and vulnerable to the goals of the main actors in criminal groups, who had instructed him to obtain valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must follow the highest standards of professional ethics and inspire trust and confidence in society.
Mr. Ditta betrayed that trust and tried to hide his profession.
Mr. Ditt's case has been investigated by Lancashire's Specially Dangerous Organized Crime Unit, which has already convicted him of three cases of cocaine possession, and now also of obstruction of justice, demonstrating our commitment to achieving a just punishment for criminals.
Let this case serve as a warning to criminals that no one is beyond the reach of the law.
We'll find you and bring you to justice.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years in prison after pleading guilty to conspiring to supply heroin, cocaine and marijuana.
