Mozambique’s security concerns are growing as a result of conflict among influential people
Under the top-down statue of Samora Machela, Mozambique’s founding president, thousands of people gathered in the centre of Maputo to chant slogans about peace at one of the rare demonstrations here.
“We want the world to come back; we want stability,” said Vanessa de Sousa, executive director of the investment company.
Fearing for the future of her country, she changed her business suit to a t-shirt decorated with the inscription “We demand security” in Portuguese, and joined the crowd on Thursday in the capital’s Independence Square.
For two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo, one of the most violent clashes since the armistice more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a well-known rebel movement, supported first by the white authorities of Rhodesia and then by the apartheid-era South African government as part of efforts to destabilize the country’s independent government.
After the 1992 armistice, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to shrink back to full-scale conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and local residents nervous.
The stakes are high for a fast-growing economy as the opening of huge offshore gas and coal reserves in the northwest could attract more than $50 billion as an investment over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the US.
The ruling Frelimo party, a leading political force since 1975, and the Renamo party blame each other for the tensions.
The Renamo party claims that the government has become the custodian of the latest clashes by attacking its members in the province of Sofala, the traditional stronghold of Renamo, on October 17.
Attacks on former rebels then escalated when government troops attacked Renamo bases and attempted to kill Afonso Dhlakamu, the group’s leader, Fernando Mazanga, a representative of Renamo, told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for initiating clashes, accusing the party of attacking a soldier.
President Armando Gebuz tried to dispel concerns about instability.
Gebuza told AFP, a French news agency, on Wednesday that Mr Dhlakama felt he was a “failure” to use “all that remains of his power to try to prove that he can impose his own decisions on the government.”
Both Frelimo and Renamo insist that they want to avoid war.
However, concerns grew after reports that Mazanga had declared Renamo's resignation from the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the Financial Times that he meant non-compliance with the agreement by the Frelimo party.
“Our goal is to return to negotiations, but with all seriousness,” Mazanga said.
Previous talks between the parties have done little to ease the tensions that have been exacerbated by a series of clashes this year.
“These are two influential people (Gebuza and Dhlakama) who have faced the brow,” said Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at the Open University and an expert on Mozambique.
None of them is a good negotiator and none of them is ready to make the necessary concessions.
The Renamo party, which is trying to achieve electoral reforms, has already said it will boycott the municipal elections scheduled for November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted this pressure as an attempt by the weakened movement to secure concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
The share of votes for Renamo has been declining since 1992, while the new party, the Democratic Movement of Mozambique (MDM), which was founded by former member Renamo, is expected to improve its performance in these elections.
Mr. Mazanga said that Mr. Gebuz, who was due to step down next year when his second term ended, wanted to destroy democracy in the country.
“He doesn’t want multi-party democracy, he doesn’t want transparent elections, he doesn’t want peace because he doesn’t want to leave the presidency,” Mazanga said.
It is unclear what the capabilities of Renault are, but it has already carried out devastating and rapid attacks on police stations and cars on a key highway leading from north to south.
Most of the clashes took place in the province of Sofala, which is several hundred kilometres north of Maputo, but includes Beirut, a port that mining companies including Rio Tinto and Vale use to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of the railroads for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railroad.
Mazanga was evasive when asked if Renamo would repeat the threat.
The Renamo party wanted to “warn the international community that things are not going very well in Mozambique,” Mazanga said.
The instability has exacerbated discontent with the government, and many people are also concerned about corruption, slow development and the recent kidnapping of people, said Fernando Lima, head of independent media company Mediacoop.
“People think that the responsibility for the future of the country lies with the government and the president, who has to find a solution to these problems,” he says.
Omar Sultan, a participant in the demonstration, said that people just want stability.
“Nobody cares about Renamo or Frelimo, they just want the renewal of the world, they want free access to the roads,” he said.
