And yet there is an interesting moment lost in the retelling of an ancient fairy tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow the orders of Europe?
Why change the yoke of London to the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the Euro crisis, the project “Europe” is officially dead.
Across the European Union, parties opposing the EU or calling for the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining strength.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party — founded this year alone — emerged from nowhere and received nearly five million votes in the September federal election, thus essentially ousting the Free Democrats (an analogue of our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis has become a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of the single currency, have led many people to think that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments operating in excessive budget deficits, which was only true for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members at exchange rates favorable to German exporters, which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe is in a disadvantageous position in terms of production capacity compared to Germany.
The only way to save money is to cut salaries and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current problems of the budget and currency is a deeper problem of Europe’s productive capacities.
As a result of the set of “green” energy measures introduced by Brussels — a cipher that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer — European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as in the United States.
This is paralyzingly unfavourable price conditions, as we have already seen in Granjmut.
No wage freeze in the world will stop the crushing victory of cheap U.S. shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, a revolt is brewing, especially in France, once the EU’s most ardent supporter.
After the war, the French political elite viewed the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on a par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving France’s ruined economy in dire straits.
The result is the anti-EU right-wing Marine Le Pen’s National Front party just won a decisive additional election, dropping the ruling Socialist Party to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote — a timely warning to British Labour that it cannot be assumed that a split between the right will automatically affect the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If – and this is very likely – anti-EU parties receive support in this election, such a bloc will be able to take a dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
Here is my opinion: the soon-to-be-growing moods against the EU and against the single currency in Europe are coming together to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become something of a vague “Europe (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several of its dependent economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will recover their own currencies.
I assume that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the US.
Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific, however, points to the likelihood that Britain will remain unattended in the cold Atlantic.
In what position does this leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region (essentially) of Little England.
Or we can protect our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland will be able to succeed within the framework of a freer European agreement, provided that we preserve our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating Norway's experience and preserving our economic independence.
The government of the Scottish National Party in Scotland is, strangely enough, the most successful political movement in Europe, directed against austerity measures, which received an impressive majority of votes in 2011 thanks to objections to cuts in spending proposed (and implemented) by the Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer and the incumbent Chancellor of the Exchequer.
