Early Sexual Maturation: Aging Earlier
African-American and Latin-American girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white counterparts, research shows.
Physical changes do not mean that sexual maturation is close.
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame.
Experts believe that the epidemic of obesity may be one of the launching mechanisms of early sexual maturation
The tendency to early sexual maturity is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be afraid if her daughter begins to form mammary glands and grow pubic hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplovitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time calming my parents — usually it doesn’t mean a quick onset of full sexual maturity,” Kaplovitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and underarm hair and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there was only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (the first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years and decreased from 12.75 in 1970.
“After the breast begins to develop, it takes at least two to three years before the menarche,” said Kaplovitz, who is also the author of the book “Early Sexual Maturation in Girls: How to Cope with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how sexual maturation will progress.
There is debate about what constitutes an actual onset of sexual maturity, but it is considered "premature" when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop - this is something that a pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression may serve as a basis for analysis by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems, such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to slower growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the level of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
The psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplovitz is wary of drugs, but admits that “sex-maturity suppression can alleviate girls’ behavioral problems and feelings that they are different from peers.”
Another big problem is clear: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They are worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they will deal with hygiene issues,” Kaplovitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter started menstruating at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we were talking about menstruation, she was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and upset that she was the first among her friends.
There are many theories about the causes of early sexual maturation.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys, as in girls, sexual maturation occurs earlier.
Kaplovitz argues that the prerequisite that has the greatest weight is the epidemic of obesity.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls aged 6 to 9, which linked the amount of fat in the body to the timing of puberty.
Other data support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latin-American girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white counterparts.
There are various explanations.
Worldwide, early sexual maturation seems to affect everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although in boys hair on the face and on the forehead appear at a younger age, the tendency to complete early sexual maturation is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors participating in the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in infants and children of childbearing age.
“We need to be careful about how we determine the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not be ashamed to receive instructions from a pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This could mean an earlier than expected conversation,” Kaplovitz explained.
If you remain calm, your child will usually react well.
Girls who bloom early need confirmation that even when this happens earlier than expected, this process is a normal part of life.
