Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarettes of pleasure.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
Further tests are needed before human trials begin, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of New York’s Well Cornell College of Medicine said the first results were encouraging.
“We very much hope that such a vaccine strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine dependence is strong enough to overcome it with these modern means,” he said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that was designed to carry genetic information for the production of anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a stable flow of antibodies.
Antibodies track any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from receiving a nicotine shot.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice, which were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activity.
And mice that were not given the vaccine “relaxed,” and this is a sign that nicotine was reaching their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
The previous tobacco vaccines had failed because they contained antibodies.
To maintain high levels of antibodies, injections had to be done so often that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystall said that if the future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they have a desire to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that it will be used by smokers to stop smoking.
“They’ll know that if they start smoking again, they won’t get pleasure from it because of the nicotine vaccine, and it can help them get rid of that habit,” he said.
