Singapore’s pawnshop owners are doing well, while the middle class is having a hard time.
In a pawn shop in Singapore’s Bendemir shopping centre, Gianni Amirthalinga puts on a gold bracelet, ring and earrings to pay for his daughter’s schooling.
“My husband and I just bought a house, so all my money is invested there,” says Mrs. Amirthalinga.
Although she earns S$3000 ($2400) per month as an administrator and her husband also works, the monthly income of the family is not enough, she says.
Indeed, the demand in various parts of Southeast Asia — where household debt is growing — is such that ValueMax, where it conducts its trade, this week became the third pawnbroker registered on Singapore’s stock exchange.
A loan secured by jewelry is not just a quick way to get money (S$1300 in the case of Mrs. Amirthaling), but also almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Usually, Singapore’s pawnbrokers charge an effective annual interest rate of 17% – just above the 15.4% offered by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnbrokers have the advantage that they do not require a credit check or proof of salary and can issue loans faster than banks.
Millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel pressured by the rising cost of living and the rapid rise in household debt and consumer debt.
After five years of sustained growth following the global financial crisis, and cheap loans fueled by free monetary policy in developed economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to make up for declining incomes as their economy slows.
This week, Standard & Poor’s, a rating agency, indicated an increase in the family’s credit rating, mainly due to the growth of the mortgage, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
It said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest ratio of household debt to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia topped the list with 80% of GDP, up from 60% in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week has barely emerged from a technical recession.
On Thursday, the data showed a continued decline in exports and a weakening of consumer demand.
“The bottom line is that with rising prices, people in the middle and bottom [income scale] will be looking for ways to top up their income wherever they can,” says Song Sung Woon, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Record high gold prices in the past two years have increased the rush with which people put their personal belongings, as they use the opportunity to get money for their family jewelry.
In Singapore, about 70 per cent of the items placed in the 200 pawnshops of the city-state are gold products.
People say, “The price of gold looks good, let’s put on Grandma’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
In Thailand, EasyMoney, the largest pawnbroker, has seen an increase in the number of customers using its branches in recent months, up to 20%.
The growth in the pawnshop business is such that ValueMax, the operator of the Bendemir branch and 15 others in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia, where it has four stores, but also outside Asia, says Yeah Li Ching, CEO of ValueMax.
The company will fund the expansion, using 60 percent of the S$66 million raised this week as a result of the placement of shares on Singapore’s stock exchange.
While some lenders have sparked criticism due to high interest rates, Ms. Yeah says that the pawnshop not only offers cheaper rates than other lenders, it also does not increase debt directly.
“Customers are putting in items they already own, and monetizing personal assets doesn’t increase household debt,” she says.
The institution is gaining increasing public recognition as a means of obtaining short-term, secured funding.
At the same time, pawnbrokers are not only used by those categories of people who are in a difficult financial situation.
Wealthy people in Singapore also use ValueMax branches, laying gold bars or Rolex watches that can give up to 60 percent of their purchase value in cash.
We see customers from all walks of life.
“They include wealthy individuals who need to borrow money for short-term commercial projects or investments, or small business enterprises who need to overcome temporary monetary difficulties,” says Ms. Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
