The industry advisory committee set up by FAU to look into the issue recommended last month that the government allow the wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on FAUs to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill, argue that there are no good security reasons for the bans.
Compliance with the restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure, as the use of devices has become widespread.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
FAU began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of interference to navigation and communication equipment when passengers began to carry FM radio receivers — high-tech gadgets of the time.
The new airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also being developed and approved by FAU as being resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi at cruising altitude for several years now.
Aircraft modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of liners have been adapted for wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Warta said.
Today’s electronic devices typically emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
Devices for reading e-books, for example, emit only minimal signals when scrolling pages.
But the signals become more powerful when the devices load or send data.
Among those who sought to ease restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company downloaded an entire airliner with their devices to read Kindle e-books and flew on it to check for problems, but did not detect them.
The members of the FAU Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of the devices posed any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Air Passengers Association said he believes device interference is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there were only separate messages from pilots confirming that the devices could create interference to aviation systems, and most of those messages were very old.
However, the committee recommended that FAU allow pilots to require passengers to turn off the devices during landings on devices in low visibility conditions.
A group of representatives of the tourism industry welcomed these changes, calling them a common-sense step towards the passengers, who are now using many technological devices.
“We are pleased that FAU recognizes that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and security,” said Roger Dow, director general of the U.S. Tourism Association.
