We have found that the vast majority of businesses are currently looking for export opportunities outside of Europe, paying particular attention to countries that are modernising and growing while EU countries are at a standstill.
They want the government to give priority to new trade ties with countries such as China, India and Brazil, rather than wasting time on a long and difficult process of reforming the EU’s tangled institutions.
When asked about their views on specific political issues, from antitrust regulation to product laws, most business leaders believed that control of these key areas of competence should be returned to Westminster.
There was a general dissatisfaction with the single market, and business representatives said that the costs of regulation from Brussels now outweigh the benefits of being in the trading zone of Europe, – agreed even 40 percent of large enterprises, traditionally the most pro-European of all companies.
Last but not least, our survey of business leaders revealed that a clear majority wants the UK to pursue a course of treaty change and trade-based relations with the EU, not politics.
This result, which has been seen among businesses of all sizes and the largest business groups, shows that business is insisting on a “significant change” that will bring power back to the UK.
The stakes are high – achieving treaty changes and more favourable conditions for the UK will provide a 16 percent shift in voting to stay in the EU.
The Prime Minister should have no doubt: this survey shows that British business supports his plan to revise the terms of UK membership in the EU.
It also shows that the business expects the revision to lead to a significant shift in the current balance of power back towards the UK.
The best conditions for British business are possible and are becoming increasingly necessary as the euro area embarks on a path of closer economic and financial integration.
Priority should be given to jobs and economic growth in the UK, and, as our survey results show, for business this means increased focus on trade and fundamental changes in Brussels’ regulatory activities.
