Scientists have shed light on how a dog’s tail movements are related to its mood.
Early studies have shown that satisfied dogs tip their tails to the right (from a dog’s point of view), while anxious dogs tip their tails to the left.
But now scientists say that other members of the dog family may notice these subtle differences in tail curling and react to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigar, a neuroscientist at Trent University, says: “It is well known that people’s left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in the formation of stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at this and other species.
He added that just as in humans, dogs have the right part of the brain controlling the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the versatile tails of other dogs, the researchers watched the animals as they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analyzed their behavior.
We will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes turn in one direction, and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed dogs videos with dogs — either naturalistic versions or silhouettes to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the tail movement and steer the tail more left or right.”
When the animals saw that the dog was not expressing anything at all moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog squeezing its tail), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was leaning mostly to the left (again, from the point of view of the dog's tail tipping), their heartbeat was racing and they looked alarmed.
Professor Vallortigara said he doesn’t think dogs intentionally communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience what movements they should be worried about, and what they should not.
He notes: “If there are several encounters with other dogs, and often their tails tipping in one direction is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts on the basis of this experience.”
The researchers say these results can give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal’s emotions.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a visiting scientist at the University of Bristol’s School of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to test whether dogs matter to the left and right sides.
Last year, a group of scientists from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a satisfied dog.
In another scientific paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when its tail was tipped to the left rather than the right, instead of becoming alarmed, the opposite behavior toward the Italian study.”
He said the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be a useful study of how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
“While there is sufficient evidence for different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details are yet to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it is likely that we will soon understand why their tails sometimes point in one direction, and sometimes in the other.
