I voted for President Obama twice, sharing hope for change.
He says Obama has allowed the obstructionism of the Republicans to nullify praiseworthy efforts.
Obstructionism can’t justify problems with Obama’s reformed health system website, drone attacks
The memoirs of Obama's 2008 campaign are a sad reminder of what could have been.
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am reading a very sad book these days.
I thought that this book would inspire me in times of sadness in the second year of medical school and give me a renewed sense of hope.
It’s called Courage to Win, and it’s a memoir of Barack Obama’s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish writing reports on my patients in the evening and go to bed, this book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people, and speeches could have captured the spirit.
The victory in the elections was impressive, and the leading news programs paused to reflect on this historic moment.
My classmates were crying for joy, and my parents were guarding all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of strategists had to come to the White House, and the people were ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, his level of support was 82%.
Then I close the book.
Returning is now a rude awakening, like pulling out of a dream.
It’s hard to remember those days of optimism — they seem like a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I dropped my first ballot, the changes have really happened.
It was something I could not even imagine.
I pay tribute to Obama for his great and varied achievements, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act to the withdrawal of our military from Iraq, the repeal of the “Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell” rule, the assassination of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstructionism has blocked too many attempts to move our country forward: immigration reform, the possibility of choosing public health and the closure of the base in Guantanamo among others.
But after countless times I’ve been on the side of the Obama administration, defending it from colleagues and peers, I’ve run out of explanations that I can provide.
I have reached the point of political despair.
The obstructionism of Republicans cannot explain the permission to eavesdrop on foreign leaders or the drone strikes on innocent children in other countries.
It cannot explain the collection of data on the privacy of Americans by the National Security Agency or the prosecution of whistleblowers exposing the government’s illegal actions.
He cannot explain the murder of American citizen Anwar al-Awlaki without trial and investigation or failure to comply with the limits of state funding and spending during presidential campaigns.
He can’t justify the report’s findings that the White House’s efforts to silence the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And lately, it can’t justify not being able to develop a simple website for more than three years after signing the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if I should have expected that.
Should I have understood at the age of 18 that leadership could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it?
It is clear that working in an elected position is not a predictable programme of action, as our public dialogue will be shaped by opposition political parties and such random events as the massacre in Newtown.
Nevertheless, all the examples I have listed above show that they were largely the choice of the administration.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney represented an incomprehensible and crude alternative, it seemed that he was unable to make a decision on his own policies or views.
I believed that in his second term, Obama, having freed himself from the pressure of future elections, justified the hopes that we have heard about for such a long time.
However, when Obama’s rating dropped below 45 percent this week, it became much harder to get back to 2008 through this book.
It makes me yearn for the many promises that have flown away.
This week I read the part of the book that describes how Clinton inflicted a stupendous defeat on Obama in the primary election in Pennsylvania.
At a meeting to analyze the causes of failure, he told his staff that they should go back to normal and remain true to their purpose.
“I want us to return our attractiveness,” he said.
We have to remember who we are.”
It's been five years, Mr. President, and I totally agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary belong exclusively to Nathaniel Morris.
