A trip through mud, rivers and jungles to provide free medical care
Dr. George Bwelle provides free medical care in rural Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend taking in hundreds of patients.
In this West African country, there are not so many doctors – only one in 5,000 people.
Vote here or through your mobile device
Dr. George Bwelle is one of CNN’s top 10 heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to become CNN’s Hero of the Year.
This man will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his father come back to life and fall back into unconsciousness, wandering around hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jameef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaounde, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that resembled itself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said George Bwell.
If we had the money, we would have taken him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father for years in overcrowded clinics and hospitals, receiving whatever treatment they could get.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle said.
You can leave the house at 5 a.m., go to the hospital to be the first, but you are not the first.
A lot of patients.
Some may die because of what they have to wait for.
The situation has not changed much since Father Bwelle passed away in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, Cameroon has only one doctor per 5,000 people.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if the Cameroonians could see a doctor, many of them would be out of pocket.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and almost three-quarters of the health care costs in this country are private.
“The only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
“And because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. George Bwelle and his team of volunteers conducted 700 free surgeries.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaounde Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his team of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday he and up to 30 other people are stuffed into vans, tied to roofs medical supplies and drive across the area to visit those in need of help from the village.
They don’t always have luck.
Many times they had to push cars across rivers and dirt.
But when they arrive, they are met like real heroes: it is a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms that only the locals can offer.
The free medical care in these villages is indeed a cause for celebration, and Bwelle with his wide smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join the fun.
The next morning, the brigade began to receive hundreds of patients.
“We take 500 people on each trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from all over the county within a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates—documents needed for school that many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evenings, the brigade conducts simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school building, municipality, or home; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative area to free up space for the next person.
Using a generator to illuminate the operational and sanitary treatment of the equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
This is an indefatigable pace, but the dedication of the brigade usually helps to support the village musicians.
“They’ve been drumming all night so we can stay awake and keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, members of the brigade go back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, has conducted 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know that their help can be of great importance to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia treatment he received would allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these weekend clinical appointments and hospital work, Bwelle also works nights at private medical clinics around Yaounde.
It is this second work, he said, that provides 60% of the funding for his non-profit organization; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t even know when he’s sleeping,” said Kathy O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, a volunteer in the Bwell group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses like O’Malley coming from the U.S. and Europe to join Bwell in carrying out his tasks, this is an opportunity for practice that they would never get at home.
“We were able to assist in operations where we helped remove blood stains or hold instruments for Dr. Bwell,” O’Malley said.
As a second-year student, you would never get such an opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medication.
But upon arrival in Yaounde, their food, transport and training pay Bwell.
“He’s a hero, no doubt,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, a near-constant workload is not a hard test.
Helping to live a happy life for others, to fulfill the promise given to his father is what brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle said.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this so that people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see what you can do to help.
