The agency "Rosbalt" deprived of the status of the media for an uncensored fight
On October 31, the Moscow court decided to recognize the invalid license on registration of the agency "Rosbalt", - writes "Lent".
Roskomnadzor insisted on the deprivation of the status of the media agency - for systematic and gross violations of the law on media.
During the process, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, in fact refusing the publication the right to make counter-arguments.
What is "Rosbalt"
CJSC "Information Agency Rosbalt" was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened its second headquarters in Moscow and a number of regional units.
The agency also has representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognized private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, “Rosbalt” has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of exclusive publications of the agency were (and still are) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the closeness of the publication to the power structures continued throughout the existence of the agency.
In addition to the fact that Rosbalt had an extensive database of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions was said that the head of the project was Natalia Chaplin - wife of Viktor Cherkesov.
At the same time, Chaplina’s role in the leadership of “Rosbalt” is not completely clear: she is most often called “the project manager”.
The general director of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolay Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt did not appear in the ratings of the federal media - neither in terms of citations nor in terms of audience.
In October, the agency took the 25th place in the rating of visits to Russian media sites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months are notes of the Kremlin's helplessness in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group "King and Joke", pogroms in the capital Birulevo.
Rosbalt's conflict with Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the media law came into force, which prohibited journalists from indiscriminate fighting.
The agency found the banned vocabulary in two videos published on the agency's website ("Gigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot desecrated the oil rigs").
The following pages describe it differently.
Roskomnadzor, on the basis of the found videos, accused Rosbalt of a gross and systematic violation of the media law and appealed to the court with a request to withdraw the license from the agency.
Rosbalt stated that the claims of the department are incorrect: first, the videos were not editorial materials, second, the parent words in them were masked, and, third, immediately after the warning the videos were removed from the site.
The agency’s representatives appealed Roskomnadzor’s claims to the world court – and when the Mosgorsud accepted Roskomnadzor’s claim on 22 October 2013, the consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, already on the 25th, the world judge made a decision not in favor of Rosbalt: the editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the Code of Administrative Offences and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each film.
Obviously, this prejudged the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow court - if you give up the idea that the outcome could have been prejudged even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate the certificate of registration of Rosbalt, effectively depriving the agency of media status.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The Agency was supported by deputies of the State Duma (the statement on behalf of the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 signed 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted at the initiative of the CPRF).
Vsevolod Bogdanov, the head of the Union of Journalists of Russia, Pavel Gusev, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists, and Mikhail Fedotov, the head of the Presidential Council on Human Rights, said of the illegal closure of the publication.
