The destruction of the stockpiles of toxic substances themselves or their chemical components should be completed by mid-2014.
According to the representative of the OPCW, the poisons are currently in sealed warehouses.
International inspectors went to Syria after more than 1,400 people were killed in a chemical attack on the outskirts of Damascus on August 21, according to the United States.
The main task of the inspectors was not to waste time – not to allow the Syrian authorities to produce more chemical weapons – and to destroy the infrastructure for mixing chemicals and ammunition equipment.
These production facilities will now be closely monitored to prevent them from being repaired.
The next milestone is mid-November: by this time, the OPCW and the Syrians must agree on a detailed plan to destroy existing stockpiles of toxic substances.
