John Kerry says in his unprecedented admission that U.S. spying “went inappropriately far”
John Kerry has demonstrated a softening of U.S. surveillance defense tactics by making an unprecedented admission that in some cases, U.S. espionage has “went inappropriately far.”
The secretary of state also admitted that he, along with Barack Obama, was guilty of being “on autopilot” during the appearance of Edward Snowden’s loud revelations about the NSA’s spying activities.
These leaks have put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic scandal with its allies.
Speaking on video at an open government conference in London, Mr. Kerry said: “There is no doubt that the president and I, as well as other members of the government, have actually perceived some things happening on autopilot because such an opportunity has already existed – both during World War II and in the very difficult years of the Cold War, September 11.”
He then became the first senior U.S. government official to admit that U.S. espionage had gone too far, but stressed that no one’s rights had been violated.
He said: “In some cases, this has gone unfavourably far.
And the president is determined to shed light on this issue and explain himself to people, and is now conducting a thorough analysis so that no one has a feeling of abuse.
I assure you, there is no abuse of innocent people in this process.”
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA acted out of good motives and that its surveillance operations saved many lives.
He added: “We are working in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.
There is radical extremism in the world, reckless and determined to kill people, explode people and attack governments.
And if you were able to intercept it, stop it before it happens?
We actually prevented plane crashes, building explosions and killing people because we were able to find out about those plans in advance.”
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will head to Europe to help resolve issues related to alleged U.S. spying abroad and convince Europeans to continue joint anti-terrorism activities with the U.S., the Senate subcommittee on European affairs chairman said on Thursday.
Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terrorist organizations due to frustration over surveillance by the National Security Agency.
“For the national security interests of the United States, it is really important that Europeans remain our supporters of our common anti-terrorism efforts,” said Murphy, a first-time Democrat who serves as chairman of the Senate’s subcommittee on international relations for European affairs, in an interview with the Washington Post.
“And I’m going to Europe to let them know that we must continue to cooperate in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger about these NSA programs.”
The news that the NSA has collected millions of phone records in Europe has worsened relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of the agency said this week that they were inaccurate and reflected a misunderstanding of the metadata that NATO allies collected and shared with the U.S.
Other disclosures included documents released by Snowden that showed the NSA was monitoring German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone, as well as the phones of some 34 other world leaders.
National Intelligence Director James Clapper defended spying on the Allies as necessary and said it was a normal affair on both sides.
Against the background of this noise, Murphy said that his office is organizing a trip of members of Congress, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hopes that the delegation will include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of other participating legislators are expected to be announced in the coming days.
According to him, the travel program is still under development.
While Murphy said the purpose of the trip was to help improve the relationship, he said some degree of “hardness from the best of motives” would also be manifested.
He said European leaders should be honest with their people about what spying programs they have used for years.
“While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they also need to accept the fact that we are not the only ones engaged in intelligence activities,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry must travel this weekend to the Middle East and Poland to address the problems of hostility to U.S. strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. intelligence activities.
